{{mergeto|totally ordered set|date=January 2019}}
Given a [[Set (mathematics)|set]] ''S'' with a [[partial order]] ≤, an '''infinite descending chain''' is an infinite, strictly decreasing sequence of elements ''x<sub>1</sub> > x<sub>2</sub> > ... > x<sub>n</sub> > ...''

As an example, in the set of [[integer]]s, the [[Chain (order theory)|chain]] −1, −2, −3, ... is an infinite descending chain, but there exists no infinite descending chain on the [[natural number]]s, as every [[Chain (order theory)|chain]] of natural numbers has a minimal element.

If a partially ordered set does not possess any infinite descending chains, it is said then, that it satisfies the [[descending chain condition]]. Assuming the [[axiom of choice]], the descending chain condition on a partially ordered set is equivalent to requiring that the corresponding [[strict order]] is [[well-founded]]. A stronger condition, that there be no infinite descending chains and no infinite [[Antichain|antichains]], defines the [[well-quasi-ordering]]s.  A totally ordered set without infinite descending chains is called [[well-order]]ed.

