[[File:Triangle diagram of rewrite rule application.pdf|thumb|Rewriting ''s'' to ''t'' by a rule ''l''::=''r''. If ''l'' and ''r'' are related by a '''rewrite relation''', so are ''s'' and ''t''. A '''simplifcation ordering''' always relates ''l'' and ''s'', and similarly ''r'' and ''t''.]]

In [[theoretical computer science]], in particular in [[automated theorem proving]] and [[term rewriting]],
a [[binary relation]] (→) on the set of [[term (logic)|term]]s is called a '''rewrite relation''' if it is [[closure (mathematics)#Closed sets|closed]] under [[term (logic)#Operations with terms|contextual embedding]] and under [[substitution (logic)#First-order logic|instantiation]]; formally: if ''l''→''r'' implies ''u''[[term (logic)#Operations with terms|[]]''l''[[Substitution (logic)#First-order logic|σ]]]<sub>''p''</sub>→''u''[''r''σ]<sub>''p''</sub> for all terms  ''l'', ''r'', ''u'', each path ''p'' of ''u'', and each [[Substitution (logic)#First-order logic|substitution]] σ. If (→) is also [[irreflexive relation|irreflexive]] and [[transitive relation|transitive]], then it is called a '''rewrite ordering''',<ref>Dershowitz, Jouannaud (1990), sect.2.1, p.251</ref> or '''rewrite [[preorder]]'''. If the latter (→) is moreover [[well-founded]], it is called a '''reduction ordering''',<ref name="DJ90:270">Dershowitz, Jouannaud (1990), sect.5.1, p.270</ref> or a '''reduction preorder'''.
Given a binary relation ''R'', its '''rewrite [[Closure (mathematics)#P closures of binary relations|closure]]''' is the smallest rewrite relation containing ''R''.<ref name="DJ90:252">Dershowitz, Jouannaud (1990), sect.2.2, p.252</ref> A transitive and reflexive rewrite relation that contains the [[Term (logic)#Operations with terms|subterm]] ordering is called a '''simplification ordering'''.<ref name="DJ90:274">Dershowitz, Jouannaud (1990), sect.5.2, p.274</ref>

